<subSubSection id="100553BFC56398723083025EE68BAFFD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="154E69AFCF0FF814695A6059A6C2A045" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F35490348D09CA99543F4905490D9C9D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">flowering in May and fruiting in September-October.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="80CBB572001D67734158BF6AE922A43B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="EC91B34B2065285041127B8233102310" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BA972065B6242D45FF8B129040C9F060" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
in openings of 
<taxonomicName id="0C0FA8096E36B2118FC01ED91FA45EFC" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus nigra" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis id="8203644E4528927554E1FFA82C655863" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pinus nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="82E21FFABC40B6E4180369F1442152C8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="00003A66DC61B6ACA4BED618E78351A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1DF262A8A1B4B6CC4E3587898278F5EE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
(Figure 
<figureCitation id="A183C0E55760D7B4CCB85573524A8913" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Distribution of the taxa. (square) Crataegus azarolus var. senobaaensis; (star) Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii var. nov. (circle) Crataegus yaltirikii (Near East topographic map-blank. svg)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.122.33002.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/302257" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="5DEF75D1F3BB35D2BC54149E79C74674" authorityName="Doenmez &amp; Oezderin" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
is endemic to 
<normalizedToken id="86345978DD59244CAEDFD313309754B2" originalValue="İzmir">Izmir</normalizedToken>
; it has a narrow distribution at 
<normalizedToken id="6B70C77485BF514427CD63D2B8579748" originalValue="Gölcük">Goelcuek</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="24B4A12E446ED93B998F29C79A437A4F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="F90495429A27F026050B9398476ABD1B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9094133684A0C0B34BC40074557A6E34" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="51185411EB2D8F53DFCB125B1AD46CB5" authorityName="Doenmez &amp; Oezderin" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
grows in openings of 
<taxonomicName id="365D0644103238C8BE8B5B82D9B767DB" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus nigra" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis id="0C776C2C3B3EA28D14D1077052A5B10B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pinus nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest between 1050 and 1120 m elevation. The basic vegetation type is maquis at lower elevations of the area. Besides this, 
<taxonomicName id="0596740F90DAEEE87CA2C19C40005E68" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus nigra" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis id="90132AC15680F907F8B53252DADEE599" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pinus nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest replaces it at higher altitudes and steppe vegetation dominates above the tree zone.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9F523D093C80B7BDD82005B379FE73B4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="5340298A903DE968590D2F4B1EF65036" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="84770AD7E568581C85068DEA34D2CDD0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The epithet of this new variety denotes the collection area, 
<normalizedToken id="F363287FCDD8F067A3B564870A1349FC" originalValue="Ödemiş">Oedemis</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="693EA80CF47E169B54C3E66CBDB41CCB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph id="DDB456823260DBA86D2FA890954CD840" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Preliminary conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E6F43174D72A7A888C8C3568BFD96886" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="887EB781979BBBA5CE61E433B82D264A" authorityName="Doenmez &amp; Oezderin" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
should be assigned to &quot;Critically Endangered&quot;, (CR B2ab(i,ii,iii,iv), D) according to the 
<bibRefCitation id="A60FFE9E8A7E19F6B4516161C81691A5" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Flora of China" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B11" refString="IUCN, 2017. Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 12. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 12. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee." url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2017">IUCN (2017)</bibRefCitation>
threat categories. The area of occupancy is estimated to be less than 10 km2 and the examined specimens are known only from alongside the road. The location is close to the picnic area of the 
<normalizedToken id="CF9C1276F710F44A5FD4519BC78D4B56" originalValue="Gölcük">Goelcuek</normalizedToken>
Lake and is under threat from fire, cutting and other anthropogenic effects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6B6D48ED7D532BB0A1EF368941EB8D65" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D4C3A58EE0C6CC0C79BECEE9E5B2646E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="254FE18A682DDE977437A9E9FF2E5811" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Two new varieties have been published by 
<bibRefCitation id="325404F89621751887CAE52BEF8A078C" author="Browicz, K" editor="Davis, PH" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="133 - 147" refId="B1" refString="Browicz, K, 1972. Crataegus L. (Rosaceae). In: Davis, PH, Ed., Flora of Turkey and the East Aegean Islands. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh: 133 - 147" title="Crataegus L. (Rosaceae)" volumeTitle="Flora of Turkey and the East Aegean Islands." year="1972">Browicz (1972)</bibRefCitation>
from Turkey under the species name of 
<taxonomicName id="0E2E2272FE0310A28F6FC84CE080A08F" genus="C." lsidName="C. aronia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aronia">
<emphasis id="FA9A598AF06BD9647F64DF3DAD88DA7A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. aronia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. These two varieties were reduced to synonym by 
<bibRefCitation id="EA6F532211C6A77993F5E8050BE5CE40" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" author="Christensen, KI" journalOrPublisher="Plant Systematics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B3" refString="Christensen, KI, 1992. Revision of Crataegussect.Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35. https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" title="Revision of Crataegussect. Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" year="1992">Christensen (1992)</bibRefCitation>
with their published name and he accepted the name 
<taxonomicName id="C51C0E0A99D8C438792B42E237D4FFD9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="azarolus">
<emphasis id="29455EB0A3DD6AF83AED5B223A08BF6F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus azarolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead of 
<taxonomicName id="247DA113557D3538BC63B403786BCCEE" genus="C." lsidName="C. aronia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aronia">
<emphasis id="F978B1729047D467BD115B4920EA68E6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. aronia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Taxonomic decisions of Christensen have been based solely on herbarium material. During the taxonomic revision of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="3EBBD92D774CDBCE20C2443565DA26E2" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2AFC6BD9AD80A7C508B4C7900415FC3F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the first author had the opportunity to observe these varieties in their habitats alongside the complete set of morphological variations of the species. Moreover, morphological studies on the large set of herbarium material in the above-mentioned herbaria and fieldwork from Greece to Iran provided more opportunity to observe all kinds of variation of 
<taxonomicName id="47E82D4A3A28BBF62620EDD9E459F5C4" genus="C." lsidName="C. azarolus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="azarolus">
<emphasis id="87A426F05B2F7129C0D5A683AD996F8D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. azarolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the closely related taxa. Consequently, based on field observations and herbarium studies on the collected materials, these two varieties, namely 
<taxonomicName id="FF3DD8A0BA8BCA942B8DFD56CDA1C1E8" authority="L." authorityName="Doenmez" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Browicz" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus var. dentata" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="azarolus" variety="dentata">Crataegus azarolus L. var. dentata</taxonomicName>
(Browicz) 
<normalizedToken id="2F8A10ED1B15C676908E63C466DBF6CF" originalValue="Dönmez">Doenmez</normalizedToken>
and 
<taxonomicName id="58BD8BB727FFD8E716CB057F6BEB625D" authority="L." authorityName="Doenmez" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Browicz" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus var. minuta" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="azarolus" variety="minuta">Crataegus azarolus L. var. minuta</taxonomicName>
(Browicz) 
<normalizedToken id="EE4ECB3671D3FBE823A43D724BC0FD28" originalValue="Dönmez">Doenmez</normalizedToken>
should be accepted as distinct taxa and they should be given as new combinations under the species name of 
<taxonomicName id="AD760AC56A6A4588678F5A5EB6D45D84" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="azarolus">
<emphasis id="1DE24BF3746DD003135F8678E43A47D8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus azarolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7645CEF8B00AE1A5F18B6F2A4C2C125F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="5BF74D392B2091E680A11912D40D8C94" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis id="BD79DD37C34EDD513A17530875469D5F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most polymorphic species amongst the Eurasian 
<taxonomicName id="504E32463AAE5F79459ED27B5D27E72B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B78639ACB5C8AF26BB2AE3FD5F8A98D6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa with respect to leaf morphology and indumentum. Due to local variations of the species and species concepts by the authors who studied 
<taxonomicName id="C7CB87DE9D1994FB786816030F3A0CC7" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2A696002A71CC941E8EFCBEF788C8622" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, many new taxa have been described. In addition, new combinations and alteration of their status have been made. Based on these taxonomic and nomenclatural novelties, both taxonomic and nomenclatural synonyms of about 200 names have been listed by 
<bibRefCitation id="1F5BA4B581579856879191893874A977" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" author="Christensen, KI" journalOrPublisher="Plant Systematics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B3" refString="Christensen, KI, 1992. Revision of Crataegussect.Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35. https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" title="Revision of Crataegussect. Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" year="1992">Christensen (1992)</bibRefCitation>
. In 
<taxonomicName id="5BB96AF6BEFFB107E85AC8A879AC4737" genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis id="5BFA09718135E2BC1F9837F70B356F6A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, extensive variations in leaf morphology and indumentum are present, whereas variations in fruit colour are limited. Fruit colour of 
<taxonomicName id="4BCC0616A06BFFFB3F8E7F869F659FB7" genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis id="808C44495F36C1CC45416C34DE4D7C32" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly red and/or with degrees of red. Specimens of the new variety, 
<taxonomicName id="4E8C1A8C56448323AC4D1711392AA6FE" genus="C." infraspecific-rank="var." lsidName="C. monogyna var. odemisii" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">C. monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
are yellow. Red and various degrees of red colour for fruit of infraspecific 
<taxonomicName id="0D25F54F1C0CF4E2F209149D8F7FD5DA" genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis id="FC08F75E3C2E416BBE9ABA161EDAF07D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa have been observed by the second author and they have hundreds of representative specimens for these fruit colours in the above-mentioned herbaria. According to observations on the fruit colour of single pyrened 
<taxonomicName id="28991BD367D7A8B63F8C8D18864AA66C" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6555A9682DDF64017D8B4032AEC749D0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxon, it is a constant character and unique in the infraspecific taxa of 
<taxonomicName id="C19808572FC7A758C590993F8B852B5E" genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis id="59A47F0174F290EBC2EDA15C4216FE94" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Hence, it is worthwhile accepting this population as a separate taxonomic status, as a variety.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="22185B51A2D218C29CC174CE97AD107D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="4DA2575C6DD96969C6F3191D7783ADD7" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus yaltirikii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="yaltirikii">
<emphasis id="CC6CF6F904379E32E2E098B553700A93" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus yaltirikii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="868AA5EB5B443CA1BD05FED339650BEC" originalValue="Dönmez">Doenmez</normalizedToken>
is a recently described new species from southeast Turkey and we found a new population of the species on the Taurus Mountain ranges, nearly 400 km away from the type locality. Climatic conditions of these two localities are different; the type locality is a cold and snowy area, whereas the recently discovered locality is characterised by hot and dry summers, rainy and warm winters. We have not yet obtained molecular works on these disjunct populations. Besides this, we assume that these populations should be local ecotypes of the species.
</paragraph>
